width="120" height="60" as="geometry" /> </mxCell> <mxCell id="Q9Nxg7FapWhMwHY416F6-50" value="<h1 style="margin-top: 0px;">Context</h1><div>This is the logical flowchart for 'hw5.asm'. Some things to note:</div><div><ul><li><span style="background-color: initial;">It generally follows the structure of the code, except some conditionals are simplified. For example, 'Is command character?' checks each character individually, so logically is 6 conditionals in a row.&nbsp;</span></li><li><span style="background-color: initial;">For processes, if the color is blue, it is a description of a one or more instructions/routines. Otherwise, it is the name of a routine in the code that can be branched to.&nbsp;</span></li><li><span style="background-color: initial;">Conditional arrows are red for false/no, green for true/yes, and otherwise, context will be included on the arrow.&nbsp;</span></li><li><span style="background-color: initial;">If a routine is branched to in many places, it will have bars on each side. The start of the subroutine will be colored orange, branches to it are colored white.</span></li></ul></div><div><br></div><div>Where I think more context is needed, I'll include a number formatted like so: (#). Here is the corresponding context to the numbers:</div><p></p><ol><li>Init loop initialized used memory range to 0x00. Finished when reached address at the end of used range.</li><li>Character limit for a command is 5 characters. any character that is not the 'return' or 'backspace' character is ignored.</li><li>A 'command character' is the first character of a command. This includes: L, l, F, f, Q, q</li><li>LED commands change led state, so anything other then quit.</li><li>The LED's correspond to bits in the leading 4 bits of the B register. So we need to remove the first byte of the ASCII, shift the trailing bytes into the leading bytes, then either shift 4 one more time, or add one to 3. These are the actions taken in the following instructions, and it achieves following mapping:</li><ul><li>LED 1 -&gt; 0x10</li><li>LED 2 -&gt; 0x20</li><li>LED 3 -&gt; 0x40</li><li>LED 4 -&gt; 0x80</li></ul><li>Here, if the command if off, we fade from on to off, so we set the LED on for the first cycle (the A loop), and off for the second cycle (the B loop). The second cycle gradually gets longer throughout the loop. NOTE: These names should be a lot better...</li></ol><p></p>" style="text;html=1;whiteSpace=wrap;overflow=hidden;rounded=0;" vertex="1" parent="1"> <mxGeometry x="-360" y="38.95" width="400" div.div: This is the logical flowchart for 'hw5.asm'. Some things to note:

li.span: It generally follows the structure of the code, except some conditionals are simplified. For example, 'Is command character?' checks each character individually, so logically is 6 conditionals in a row.
For processes, if the color is blue, it is a description of a one or more instructions/routines. Otherwise, it is the name of a routine in the code that can be branched to.
Conditional arrows are red for false/no, green for true/yes, and otherwise, context will be included on the arrow.
If a routine is branched to in many places, it will have bars on each side. The start of the subroutine will be colored orange, branches to it are colored white.

div.div: Where I think more context is needed, I'll include a number formatted like so: (#). Here is the corresponding context to the numbers:

ol.li: Init loop initialized used memory range to 0x00. Finished when reached address at the end of used range.
Character limit for a command is 5 characters. any character that is not the 'return' or 'backspace' character is ignored.
A 'command character' is the first character of a command. This includes: L, l, F, f, Q, q
LED commands change led state, so anything other then quit.

The LED's correspond to bits in the leading 4 bits of the B register. So we need to remove the first byte of the ASCII, shift the trailing bytes into the leading bytes, then either shift 4 one more time, or add one to 3. These are the actions taken in the following instructions, and it achieves following mapping:

Here, if the command if off, we fade from on to off, so we set the LED on for the first cycle (the A loop), and off for the second cycle (the B loop). The second cycle gradually gets longer throughout the loop. NOTE: These names should be a lot better...

div.div:
LED Commands
L1: Toggle LED 1 on (instant)
F1: Toggle LED 1 off (instant)
L2: Toggle LED 2 on (4s fade)F2: Toggle LED 2 off (4s fade)
L3: Toggle LED 3 on (instant)F3: Toggle LED 2 off (instant)
L4: Toggle LED 4 on (instant)F4: Toggle LED 4 off (instant)
QUIT: Quit (exit to typewriter)
